# FakeStoreAPI Products Pipeline

![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.11%2B-blue)
![Tests](https://img.shields.io/badge/Tests-pytest-green)
![Async](https://img.shields.io/badge/Async-aiohttp-purple)

A high-performance data pipeline that fetches product data from the FakeStoreAPI, stores it as a structured CSV dataset, and performs category-level analytics.

The project is designed with **scalability, resilience, and API efficiency** in mind, using asynchronous requests, retry logic, and incremental streaming.

---

## 📦 Features

- 🚀 Async product fetching using `aiohttp`
- 🔁 Retry mechanism with exponential backoff
- 📊 Category-level analytics engine
- 🧩 Pydantic-based data validation
- 💾 Streaming CSV writes (memory efficient)
- 🔄 Resume support (append mode)
- 🧪 Automated test suite with `pytest`

---

## 🏗 Architecture Overview

### Data Ingestion Layer
- Fetches product data via `GET /products/{id}`
- Sequential ID discovery (no bulk endpoint used)
- Handles missing products gracefully (404 or null responses)
- Streams results incrementally to disk

### Analytics Layer
- Reads structured CSV dataset
- Computes category-level aggregations
- Generates statistical insights

---

## 📁 Project Structure

```text
.
├── fetch_products.py        # Async data ingestion pipeline
├── analyze_products.py      # Analytics engine
├── models.py                # Pydantic data models
├── products_processed.csv   # Output dataset
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
└── tests/
```

---

## ⚙️ Installation

### Requirements
- Python 3.11+
- Internet connection

### Setup

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

---

## 🚀 Usage

### 1. Fetch Products

```bash
python fetch_products.py
```

Output:

```text
products_processed.csv
```

#### Overwrite mode

```bash
python fetch_products.py --mode overwrite
```

#### Append mode (resume run)

```bash
python fetch_products.py --mode append
```

#### Help / options

```bash
python fetch_products.py --help
```

Available options:
- `--max-concurrency`
- `--max-retries`
- `--retry-backoff`
- `--chunk-size`
- `--start-id`
- `--stop-after-empty-batches`
- `--max-id`

---

### 2. Run Analytics

```bash
python analyze_products.py
```

Or:

```bash
python analyze_products.py --input products_processed.csv
```

### 📊 Analytics Output

- Products per category
- Average price per category
- Average rating per category
- Min/max price per category
- Total inventory value per category
- Highest/lowest rated products per category
- Best/worst performing categories

---

## 🧪 Testing

Run tests:

```bash
pytest tests -v
```

Run with coverage:

```bash
pytest --cov=. --cov-report=term-missing
```

---

## 📊 Dataset Schema

| Column        | Description            |
|---------------|------------------------|
| id            | Product identifier     |
| title         | Product title          |
| price         | Product price          |
| description   | Product description    |
| category      | Product category       |
| image         | Product image URL      |
| rating_rate   | Product rating         |
| rating_count  | Number of ratings      |

---

## 🧠 Design Decisions

### Why use the single-product endpoint?

This project intentionally uses:

```
GET /products/{id}
```

instead of the bulk endpoint.

### Benefits:
- Avoids redundant full dataset downloads
- Streams results incrementally
- Improves fault tolerance
- Enables resume support (append mode)
- Provides fine-grained retry control

---

## ⚠️ Assumptions

- Product IDs are numeric and sequential
- Missing products may return:
  - HTTP 404
  - HTTP 200 with `null` body
- Both are treated as non-existent products

